<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="6b031175fe31c947775d504492c932ac" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Turning Gollum into a Beverly Hills Ninja<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.88)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14074'>Chris "Mental Warg" Tubman</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14074&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 6, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Recently a lot of people have been posting &#39;Ninja Gollum&quot; shadows on this site.  I have a special place in my heart for this shadow since I played it back in April to win a TOC.  Of couse back then I thought of Gollum more as a pimp and You&#39;re a Liar and a Theif as the &#39;pimp slap&#39;... Of course that was rediculous and never caught on so now everyone just refers to it as &#39;Ninja Gollum&#39;.  I suppose that&#39;s appropriate imagery since when things work out right this little sneak can wipe out a whole fellowship with about 2 pool and 6 cards in one turn... It is not pretty.<br />
<br />
I am now writing this article to help people deal with this shadow.  Why you might ask?  Well it&#39;s just demoralizing and humiliating if you let your entire fellowship get wiped off of the table by one 5 strength minion... don&#39;t you think?<br />
<br />
Ninja Gollum or Ju Jitsu Gollum as he&#39;s apparently called in Brazil has always had some weaknesses; some more apparent than others.  The release of Mount Doom and Shelob, Her Ladyship helped to counter some of these weaknesses such as the popular Faramir, SOD causing it&#39;s recent resurgence in the tournament scene.<br />
<br />
Still, I think if you know how to play against it the shadow is not that strong.  So I&#39;m just going to take a minute to cover a few different strategies to shut the deck down and make your gaming experience a little bit better... After all no one wants his entire fellowship wiped off of the board in one turn by a 5 strength minion... well at least no one that I know.<br />
<br />
Here are some various ways to stop that little ninja in his tracks changing him from Jackie Chan into Chris Farley.<br />
<br />
#1) Condition Removal:  <br />
<br />
This is probably the easiest or most obvious way to deal with the gollum wounding package.  Taking out key cards such as Promise Keeping and They Stole It essentially sends the one man wrecking crew packin.  The problem with this method is that most &#39;Ninja Gollum&#39; decks pack 4 x each of the key conditions.  Promise keeping is the #1 target as it effectively doubles all of the wounds, including threats, unless you are tricksy yourself (see below)... <br />
<br />
Any kind of condition removal will work.  Grown Suddenly is nice, but the pool may allow them to drop Sauron or Shelob on you.  Also, it&#39;s no fun to play a grown for 5 and then have them replay Promise Keeping and They Stole It almost immediately.  ALso, if they are rockin the Ninja they will target G-dalf first with YaLaaT, etc if they are not retarded.  Any kind of more permanent condition removal is better such as Galadriel or my personal favorite Elrond with Vilya.<br />
<br />
Elrond with Vilya is probably the single most effective way to stop Promise Keeping turn after turn.  Watch out for Fear and Tower Assassin as most Ninja Gollum players will be aware of the Elrond problem and pack their own counter bams.<br />
<br />
#2) Elimination via Direct Damage:  <br />
<br />
Well if your opponent does get Gollum and his the condition lock down (TSI and PK) up and running you might just have to take Gollum out before the skirmish phase.  Using any number of methods from great day, great hour/greenleaf to gondor bowmen, stone tower, citadel of the stars, Eowyn, LoI (not to be used when shelob is on the board ;-))... You get the picture.  Personally the most enjoyable method of wiping that tricksy little tard out is to use smeagol with don&#39;t look at them; the inherent irony is priceless.  This all seems like a lot of fuss for a 5 strength minion, but often times a couple of exertions/cards are well worth it.  It beats a decimated fellowship. <br />
<br />
Oh and remember if you plan on using a skirmish action to wound him to death such as Eowyn, LoI, Don&#39;t Look at Them, Paths, Knife of the Galadrhrim whatever just make sure that that little freak is exhausted when the skirmish starts so that you give them no opportunity to use They Stole It.<br />
<br />
#3) Prevention of skirmish: special abilities<br />
<br />
Well if you can&#39;t get rid of the conditions and you can&#39;t get rid of gollum you can always just neuter him with Faramir.<br />
<br />
Faramir, SOD: This is the classic way to stop Gollum.  All you need to do is assign gollum to Faramir, SOD and the shadow player cannot use They Stole It or any other tricks, most times he can&#39;t even win a skirmish.  This counter has been somewhat eliminated post doom due to Shelob, Her Ladyship, but Faramir can still save you more often than not especially if you keep the web off of the table.  As a note of interest, if you happen to let Gollum win his skirmish vs. Faramir the shadow player may still use You&#39;re a Liar and a Theif (since it is a response: and not a skirmish event) so be aware of that.<br />
<br />
#4) Skirmish Cancelling:<br />
<br />
So you can&#39;t get rid of the conditions, you can&#39;t get rid of gollum, you don&#39;t play faramir, sod or haven&#39;t drawn him yet... What can you do?  You can just stealth it... Yes I know stealths don&#39;t exist anymore... or do they?<br />
<br />
Gandalf&#39;s Staff: Well it will cost you 2 exertions, but no one will die and Promise Keeping won&#39;t rape you.  Often times it&#39;s worth it until you can draw you&#39;re Grown Suddenly Tall, etc.. <br />
<br />
Any other currently legal way to cancel a skirmish anything from Curse Them, to Escape, to Rohirrim Helm (note: this works best if gollum is exhausted or your opponent is an idiot) will also work.  If it requires a specific companion, like Gandalf, however, Shelob, HL will still rain on your little parade.<br />
<br />
#5) Wound Prevention:  <br />
<br />
Now we&#39;re getting ourselves in trouble we have no way to stop skirmishes, skirmish actions, no way to remove the little bugger with direct damage or discarding... and to top it off his conditions are out....  Well at this point you are in a bit of trouble, but you still have options.<br />
<br />
Wound prevention is also a fairly effective way to slow down the Ninja beating.  Things like Dwarven Bracers, Intimidate, Sapling of the White Tree, etc... will prevent the wounds from being placed which in turn prevents Promise Keeping from kicking in.  <br />
<br />
One of the best is Gimli&#39;s Helm as you can use it if someone does succumb to a wicked ninja kick to prevent all threat wounds stopping PK in it&#39;s tracks.  Faramir, WP is also good for this. <br />
<br />
Smeagol, Slinker is actually one of the best ways to deal with that little prick.  All you do is assign him to slinker and add a burden as your first skirish action... Now smeagol takes no wounds so the shadow player is virtually helpless.  Similarily, and I am hesitant to mention this, but swept away and an exhausted wraith will also do the trick.<br />
<br />
#6) Random Tricks... <br />
<br />
Sometimes you just have to be tricksy... This would include using Thrarin to block.  If you read Promise Keeping it only triggers off of wounds taken by &#39;companions&#39; in a skirmish.  So if Thrarin dies... The threat wounds can be taken without the extra exertions.  Similarily, using the One Ring to soak threats as burdens prevents Promise Keeping from triggering as well.  And I just thought of this one, but using White Arrows to empty your opponents hand in the archery phase will also leave that twisted joker helpless as no cards = no they stole it...<br />
<br />
A couple of don&#39;ts:<br />
<br />
Whatever you do don&#39;t EVER assign Gollum to Boromir, Bearer of Council... Since when he wounds himself at the start of the skirmish Promise Keeping feeds off of that also since a companion is taking a wound during a skirmish with a gollum companion.<br />
<br />
Don&#39;t EVER assign Gollum to a hobbit companion when They Stole It is on the board.  3 cards = 2 wounds = or 4 with Promise Keeping out.  Doing this will usually result in a dead hobbit and an exhausted fellowship (with a resonable number of threats).<br />
<br />
Don&#39;t EVER just let gollum win for the hell of it... You need to be aware that You&#39;re a Liar and a Theif can off your power companions if you are sloppy and let the little bugger win a skirmish, especially if they have been using Desrt Lord to exhaust your faramir or gandalf, etc...<br />
<br />
And finally, Don&#39;t EVER remind your opponent that Shelob also triggers Promise Keeping!<br />
<br />
Well that&#39;s about all I can think of right now.  I realize that some of these things are extremely obvious, but since &#39;Ninja Gollum&#39; has cought on more recently with the release of the new Shelob and some of the other fun cards I just thought I&#39;d give people some pointers on how to defeat the shadow.  Hopefully, some of this was helpful to some people. <br />
<br />
See everyone at worlds.<br />
<br />
Tubman <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=5763&view=1&PHPSESSID=6b031175fe31c947775d504492c932ac'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=6b031175fe31c947775d504492c932ac'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=6b031175fe31c947775d504492c932ac'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
